IOWA HEALTH SYSTEM AND SUBSIDIARIES (D/B/A UNITYPOINT HEALTH) IOWA HEALTH SYSTEM IS AN IOWA NONPROFIT CORPORATION FORMED IN DECEMBER 1994. IOWA HEALTH SYSTEM AND ITS SUBSIDIARIES PROVIDE INPATIENT AND OUTPATIENT CARE AND PHYSICIAN SERVICES FROM SIXTEEN HOSPITAL FACILITIES AND VARIOUS AMBULATORY SERVICE AND CLINIC LOCATIONS IN IOWA AND ILLINOIS. PRIMARY, SECONDARY AND TERTIARY CARE SERVICES ARE PROVIDED TO RESIDENTS OF IOWA, ILLINOIS AND ADJACENT STATES. ON APRIL 16, 2013, IOWA HEALTH SYSTEM BEGAN BEING PUBLICLY KNOWN AS UNITYPOINT HEALTH (THE SYSTEM). THIS NAME CHANGE REFLECTS THE TRANSFORMATION OF CLINICAL PROCESSES UNDERWAY WITHIN THE SYSTEM AND THE ADAPTATION TO BETTER ADDRESS THE HEALTH CARE NEEDS OF COMMUNITIES, INCLUDING BUILDING A MODEL OF DELIVERING HEALTH CARE THAT COORDINATES CARE AROUND THE PATIENT WHILE FOCUSING ON IMPROVING THE QUALITY OF CARE AND REDUCING COSTS. THE LEGAL NAME OF THE PARENT REMAINS IOWA HEALTH SYSTEM, WITH THE UNITYPOINT HEALTH NAME REFLECTING A DOING BUSINESS AS (D/B/A).

THE TRANSACTIONS REPORTED BETWEEN GIA AND THE RELATED ORGANIZATIONS LISTED ON LINES 2(1)-2(3) OF PART V INVOLVE THE PAYMENT OF ROYALTIES BY THE RELATED ORGANIZATIONS TO GIA FOR THE USE OF CERTAIN INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY. THESE RELATED ORGANIZATIONS ARE NOT TAX EXEMPT UNDER SECTION 501(C)(3) OF THE CODE, BECAUSE THEY ARE NOT LOCATED OR OPERATING IN THE UNITED STATES. HOWEVER, IF THESE ORGANIZATIONS WERE TAX EXEMPT UNDER SECTION 501(C)(3) OF THE CODE WITH THE SAME EXEMPT PURPOSES AS GIA, THESE ORGANIZATIONS WOULD HAVE NO UNRELATED BUSINESS INCOME, SINCE ALL OF THEIR INCOME AND ACTIVITIES ARE IDENTICAL IN CHARACTER TO GIA'S TAX-EXEMPT INCOME AND ACTIVITIES. ACCORDINGLY, THESE ROYALTY PAYMENTS ARE NOT TREATED AS UNRELATED BUSINESS INCOME FOR GIA UNDER SECTION 512(B)(13) OF THE CODE. THE TRANSACTIONS REPORTED BETWEEN GIA AND THE RELATED ORGANIZATIONS LISTED WITH TRANSACTION TYPE S ARE ASSOCIATED WITH THE PROVISION OF GRADING AND MANAGEMENT SERVICES BY GIA. THESE GRADING SERVICES ARE PERFORMED IN GIA'S ORDINARY COURSE OF BUSINESS AS DESCRIBED IN SCHEDULE O, PART III, LINE 4B. THE TRANSACTIONS REPORTED BETWEEN GIA AND THE RELATED ORGANIZATIONS LISTED WITH TRANSACTION TYPE R ARE ASSOCIATED WITH RESEARCH SERVICES.

The Foundation and the Fellowship entered into an agreement on January 1, 2012, whereby the Fellowship agrees to provide essential administrative services and assign the Fellowship employees upon mutual agreement of both parties to work at the direction of the officers and board of directors of the Foundation to preform administrative tasks for the Foundation and its responsibilities under this agreement. Each assigned employee shall remain and be considered for legal purposes an employee of the Fellowship and merely assigned to render services to the Foundation to fulfill compatible tax-exempt purposes. The Foundation shall reimburse the Fellowship for the services provided by said assigned employee of the Fellowship. The reimbursement for those services amounted to $105,000 and $101,000 in 2013 and 2012, respectively. These transactions were eliminated in consolidation. Transactions between Word of Life and the Foundation in addition to those disclosed elsewhere in the footnotes at and during the year ended December 31, 2013, consisted of: (1) contributions received from the Foundation totaling $5,938,974, which includes $3,000,000 of loan forgiveness; and (2) interest on the outstanding note payable paid to the Foundation totaling $247,500.
